<DOC><DOCNO> AP890118-0008 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0107EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0777 01-18 1039</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,1072</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: ADDS Cruickshank Garcia and Sheatsley; Separates moved for AMsas a0669 on Wilson, a0736 on Bentsen, a0756 on Allott, a0763 on Probstand as a0762 on Cruickshank Garcia. Probst also moved on the business wire.</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhotos MCA1,DN2,DN5</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><BYLINE>Trey Wilson</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Trey Wilson, a character actor who appeared onstage and screen in recent hits from ``Raising Arizona'' to ``BullDurham,'' died Monday of a cerebral hemorrhage at age 40.   Wilson also appeared in ``A Soldier's Story,'' ``F-X'' and ``TheHouse on Carroll Street.'' Two other films _ ``Welcome Home'' and``Miss Firecracker'' _ have not yet been released, along with thejust-completed ``Great Balls of Fire,'' the Jerry Lee Lewis story.   He appeared on stage in ``The Front Page'' at Lincoln Center,``Custom of the Country'' at the Second Stage and ``The DebutanteBall'' at Manhattan Theater Club. His Broadway credits included``Peter Pan,'' ``Tintypes,'' ``The First'' and ``Foxfire.''</TEXT><BYLINE>Lloyd Bentsen Sr.</BYLINE><DATELINE>EDINBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lloyd M. Bentsen Sr., an early developerof Texas' Lower Rio Grande Valley whose son, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, wasthe Democratic vice-presidential candidate last year, was killedTuesday in a traffic accident. He was 95.   Bentsen held nearly 50,000 acres of farms and six ranchesscattered over a South Texas empire he started in 1920.   By the 1970s his holdings ranged from farm, cattle, oil, gas andnursery operations to control of six banks, stock in other banks andland sales entimated at $1 million a month. Although he had sold hisbank holdings, Bentsen continued farming, running 5,000 head ofcattle, operating a nursery, taking in oil and gas revenues andmanaging a real estate business.</TEXT><BYLINE>Gordon Allott</BYLINE><DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gordon Allott, a former U.S. senator,died Tuesday of cancer at the age of 82.   Allott graduated from the University of Colorado in Boulder in1927 and from its law school in 1929.   During World War II, he was a major in the Army Air Corps.   Allott served terms as Lamar city attorney, district attorney andColorado's lieutenant governor from 1951-1955. He was also vicechairman of the state Board of Parole.   Allott, a Republican, served three terms in the U.S. Senate from1955 to 1973. He also worked on the Appropriations and Interiorcommittees. Allott was the Senate sponsor for the Colorado RiverBasin Storage Act of 1968, which provided for construction of fiveColorado water projects and the Central Arizona Project.</TEXT><BYLINE>Gerald Probst</BYLINE><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gerald G. Probst, 65, a decorated World WarII pilot who later rose through the corporate ranks to becomechairman of Sperry Corp., died Sunday. The cause of death had notbeen determined as of Tuesday.   Probst joined the Air Force in 1942 and commanded a B-24 bomberin World War II missions over Europe. He was awarded thedistinguished flying cross and the air medal with three oak leafclusters.   Probst joined Sperry Univac in St. Paul, Minn., in 1961. He wasnamed to positions of increasing responsibility over the nextdecade, being promoted to a divisional presidency in 1971.   Probst became corporate vice president in 1974, executive vicepresident in 1975, and company president in 1980. He was electedchairman of the board of Sperry in 1982.   Probst was named chairman and chief executive officer of Sperryin September 1986 when the $5 billion computer and defense systemscompany merged with Burroughs Corp. to form Uinsys. He retired a fewmonths later but continued to serve as a member of UinsysInternational's advisory board.</TEXT><BYLINE>George Tweed</BYLINE><DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   George Tweed, a World War II Navyradioman who eluded Japanese forces on the Pacific island of Guamfor more than two years and became the subject of a movie, diedMonday in a car accident in Northern California at age 86.   When Japanese forces overran Guam in 1941, Tweed and severalothers slipped into the jungle rather than surrender. He became thelone survivor after the others were captured and killed.   Tweed managed to elude Japanese soldiers for two years and sevenmonths, providing information to American forces that recaptured theisland in 1944. He was awarded the Legion of Merit.   His story was told in the book ``Robinson Crusoe USN,'' and the1962 movie ``No Man is an Island,'' starring Jeffrey Hunter asTweed.</TEXT><BYLINE>Fred Cooper</BYLINE><DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Fred Cooper, an editor with the SanfordHerald, died Tuesday of lung cancer. He was 58.   Cooper was editorial page editor of the newspaper.   He worked for the New Orleans Times-Picayune and the WashingtonEvening Star early in his career.   Cooper spent 15 years as sports information director at StetsonUniversity in DeLand and earlier was a psychological warfare writerwith the U.S. Army.   Most recently, Cooper played a key role in development of theFlorida Sports Hall of Fame and helped cover sports events for TheAssociated Press.</TEXT><BYLINE>Jorge Cruickshank Garcia</BYLINE><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Congressman Jorge Cruickshank Garcia,co-founder and leader for two decades of the Popular SocialistParty, died Tuesday of a brain tumor Tuesday at age 73.   With the late Vicente Lombardo Toledano, Cruickshank Garciahelped found the party in 1948 and had been its secretary-generalsince 1968.   Cruickshank Garcia was serving his fourth term in Congress,representing Mexico City's Federal District, similar to the Districtof Columbia in the United States. He was a senator from 1976-1982.</TEXT><BYLINE>Paul Sheatsley</BYLINE><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Paul B. Sheatsley, an expert in the field ofsurvey research, died Sunday after a long bout with empheysema. Hewas 72.   Sheatsley began his career in survey research as an interviewerfor the Gallup organization. He joined the National Opinion ResearchCenter at the University of Chicago in 1942 and directed thecenter's New York office until 1961, when he became head of theresearch center's main office in Chicago. He was president of theresearch center from 1967-68.   He supervised a number of innovative studies, including one onthe public reaction to the assassination of President John F.Kennedy in 1963. He was known for his work in survey design andmethods and in health care and race relations research.</TEXT></DOC>